WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.260
So last June, as I was strolling by Lake Lugano on the way to ICML 25, I was wondering, how

00:00:06.260 --> 00:00:08.520
are we going to improve on our CAR-T cell therapy?

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:09.980
There's a session.

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:11.980
So I'll present the data.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:14.200
Why do we want to improve on this?

00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:21.000
We know that loss of CD19 antigen is seen in about a third of patients with DLBCL post-CAR-T

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:21.500
relapse.

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:25.800
So adding another targeted epitope makes sense.

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:31.500
So what I'm going to review are the three sort of what I feel are frontrunners, the

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:34.040
CHI product, the Janssen, and the Miltaini product.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:40.120
So the CHI product is interesting because it's a bisistronic leniviral vector.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:48.620
It encodes an anti-CD19 CAR that has a CD28 co-stimulatory domain and an anti-CD20 CAR

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:51.700
that has a 4-1-BB co-stimulatory domain.

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:56.960
So what was primarily presented was the phase.

00:00:56.980 --> 00:00:59.800
Phase 1B portion, the dose expansion.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:07.800
And I am moving fast because I'm trying to review three presentations in seven minutes.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.140
What I will point out is that the dose level three, there were 26 patients.

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:22.020
They did allow patients who, this was second-line therapy, and that was approximately half of

00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:23.260
the patients in that group.

00:01:23.260 --> 00:01:26.880
And they did allow bridging.

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:31.040
They did allow bridging therapy, which, again, approximately half the patients received that.

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:33.640
Oh, sorry, here it is.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:37.380
So 58% in dose level three received the bridging therapy.

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:42.120
There were some patients who had prior CD19 CAR-Ts allowed on trial.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:45.880
So what did we see?

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:52.840
We actually saw pretty low incidence of grade three ICANS or CRS.

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:54.840
So 4%, 8%.

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:56.960
All results.

00:01:56.980 --> 00:01:59.560
So this is a little bit more overwhelming.

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:00.560
What about responses?

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:05.760
So on the left of this slide, they're looking at the CAR-naive patients who are in the dose

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:06.760
level three.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:12.120
78% achieved a CR, the others you can see.

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:20.280
And looking at dose levels one and two, 36% achieved a CR.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:26.420
If you look at the 18 patients at dose level three who are CAR-naive, they're a six-month,

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:27.360
five-month, six-month, six-month, six-month, six-month, six-month, six-month, six-month, six-month,

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:35.160
duration of CR rate was still at 71.4%.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:39.760
So that was a brief summary of the first dual CAR.

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:47.660
So next we get into the bispecific CARs where the two epitope binding domains are within

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:50.320
a single transmembrane protein.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:53.200
Here I'll review the J&J data.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:56.200
Initially this was, there was a Chinese study.

00:02:56.200 --> 00:03:01.020
It was a study that looked at enlarged B-cell lymphoma that had a very high response rate

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:06.540
at 86%, which led to this leading to this trial.

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:16.940
So in this global phase 1B study, the presentation mostly focused on the fixed dose at 75 million

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:21.960
CAR-T cells, and there were 25 patients in that group.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:25.980
Again, I will point out that it did allow one patient.

00:03:25.980 --> 00:03:33.360
There were patients who had only had one prior line of therapy, and in the fixed dose cohort

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:35.940
that was right at 50%.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:43.480
They also allowed bridging therapy, which again was slightly over 50% of patients.

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:46.000
The rate of CRS was actually quite low.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.540
The grade three CRS was two patients.

00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:55.760
With regards to ICANNs, again, very low toxicity was seen.

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:58.640
What about the response rate?

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:05.340
So when you look at the recommended phase two dose, they saw a 77% CR rate, or an overall

00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:13.520
response rate, you know, closing in on 100%, so quite well.

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:18.940
Looking at a swimline plot, you know, you see very good responses, and some are very

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:23.440
durable at the time of the report.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:25.760
So moving on to the third CAR.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:29.660
And I have two minutes and 34 seconds to review this.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:30.660
So XamtaCell.

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:40.840
Again, this is a single, or it's a dual epitope-binding single transmembrane protein.

00:04:40.840 --> 00:04:44.120
What is unique about it is that it is a fresh product.

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:46.820
It is not pro-preserved.

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:55.540
So the vein-to-vein time on average was 13 days, so a much more abbreviated time to infusion.

00:04:55.540 --> 00:05:02.940
They did allow bridging chemotherapy, but that was only in 5% of the patients.

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:07.780
They were fairly high-risk patients in general.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:08.780
You always have to wonder.

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:13.320
You're giving bridging chemotherapy while patient's product is being made, so there's

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.320
a risk there.

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:19.100
But what they did demonstrate is that all of the patients were treated.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:25.320
91.3% were within specification, and the other 9% were still treated with their plant-based

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:27.520
product.

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:32.020
And again, the viral copy number, important to note that it's not too high, which increases

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:35.120
risk with your product.

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:36.120
So what did we see?

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:41.760
An overall response rate of 72, 73%.

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:47.740
The CR rate was 50%.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:52.160
When you look at the medium progression-free survival, it was 9 months, but in the, of

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.100
course, with the CR group, it was greater than that.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:06:02.940
When you look at the median duration of response, again, 11.4 months.

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:04.860
What about toxicity?

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:09.720
There was a single patient with grade 3 ICANs.

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:12.080
There were, no, actually two patients.

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:17.200
There were no patients who developed grade 3 CRS.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:22.700
So in summary, and I'm keeping it under seven minutes, these are three what I consider front-running

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:24.880
products.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:54.660
So the CRS was very manageable, typically low-grade.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:55.500
The CRS was very good.

